<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 406px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">Model Protocols According to Methods of Measurement</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p>This approach involves modeling the structure considering the guidelines of the rules of measurement to be considered on the project.&nbsp;</p>
<p>In some cases, those are not aligned with the default behavior of authoring tools and demand adjustments on each element, which can be extra time-consuming.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Nonetheless, it offers clear advantages over the 2D approach, considering that not only the results remain consistent with rules of measurement, but also leverages the full benefits of a BIM project.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div>